      { q: "How do you solve the equation 3x - 7 = 11?", a: "Step 1: Add 7 to both sides: 3x - 7 + 7 = 11 + 7, giving 3x = 18. Step 2: Divide both sides by 3: x = 18 ÷ 3 = 6. Step 3: Check by substituting back: 3(6) - 7 = 18 - 7 = 11 ✓. The answer is x = 6." },
      { q: "What does it mean to factorise an expression?", a: "Factorisation means writing an expression as a product of its factors. For example, 12x + 8 can be factorised as 4(3x + 2) because 4 is the highest common factor of 12 and 8. Factorisation is the reverse of expanding brackets. It simplifies expressions and is essential for solving quadratic equations." },
      { q: "How do you solve simultaneous equations?", a: "Simultaneous equations are two equations with two unknowns. Method 1 (Substitution): Rearrange one equation to express one variable in terms of the other, then substitute into the second equation. Method 2 (Elimination): Multiply equations so that one variable has the same coefficient, then add or subtract the equations to eliminate that variable. Solve for the remaining variable, then substitute back." }
