    qa: [
      { q: "What are the symbols of South Sudan's national identity?", a: "South Sudan's national symbols include: (1) The national flag — three horizontal stripes (black for the people, red for the blood of martyrs, green for the land) with a blue triangle (for the Nile) and a gold star (for unity); (2) The national anthem — 'South Sudan Oyee!'; (3) The coat of arms — features an African fish eagle, a shield, and spears; (4) The national motto — 'Justice, Liberty, Prosperity'; (5) Independence Day — 9 July; (6) The capital city — Juba." },
      { q: "What is the difference between citizenship and nationality?", a: "Citizenship is a legal status — it means being a recognised member of a state with specific rights and responsibilities (e.g., the right to vote, hold a passport, and access public services). Nationality can refer to citizenship but also has a broader cultural meaning — it refers to a person's sense of belonging to a nation or ethnic group. In South Sudan, a person can be a South Sudanese citizen (legal status) while also identifying with their ethnic nationality (e.g., Dinka, Nuer, Bari)." },
      { q: "How can South Sudan build a unified national identity while respecting ethnic diversity?", a: "South Sudan can build national unity while respecting diversity by: (1) Promoting a shared national narrative — celebrating the common struggle for independence; (2) Using national symbols and celebrations to foster belonging; (3) Ensuring equal representation of all ethnic groups in government; (4) Promoting national languages (English and Arabic) while respecting local languages; (5) Teaching national history and citizenship in schools; (6) Ensuring equitable distribution of resources; (7) Promoting inter-ethnic dialogue and reconciliation; (8) Celebrating cultural diversity as a national strength." },
      { q: "Why is national identity important for a country like South Sudan?", a: "National identity is important for South Sudan because: (1) It creates a sense of unity and belonging among diverse ethnic groups; (2) It provides a foundation for peaceful coexistence and conflict resolution; (3) It motivates citizens to contribute to national development; (4) It gives the country a distinct identity in the international community; (5) It helps overcome the divisions created by decades of civil war; (6) A strong national identity can reduce ethnic tensions by emphasising what citizens have in common rather than what divides them." }
    ],
